This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category cs.CL (Computation and Language) because it deals with natural language processing and specifically focuses on latent tree learning models for sentence representation. Additionally, the paper mentions downstream tasks, which are often associated with the field of computational linguistics. 

The paper also involves machine learning techniques, such as shift-reduce parsing and chart parsing, which are commonly used in the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). 

Furthermore, the paper discusses the induced trees learned by the models, which could potentially fall under the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as it involves the analysis of neural networks. 

Finally, the paper mentions the use of syntax trees, which could potentially relate to the sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision) as syntax trees are sometimes used in image captioning tasks. However, this is less likely than the other sub-categories mentioned above.
